    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute anomalies for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) as follows: first compute global P95 and P5 for each full series (use all rows for that group). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-20 07:02:05 UTC to 2024-01-20 07:32:05 UTC. For each group, detect 'high' anomalies where value >= global P95 and 'low' anomalies where value <= global P5 within the incident window. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name,anomaly_type) produce: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, min_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Return rows sorted by anomaly_count descending, limit to top 20. Also return the total number of metric rows within the incident window."}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous anomaly scan over all metric groups we found many infra/messaging and DB anomalies (rabbitmq, session-db, catalogue-db, etc.). Restricting attention to the candidate service list (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) reveals these service-level signals inside the incident window: orders shows elevated error counts and a drop to zero diskio (low) for many points; user and payment show socket anomalies (mostly low), catalogue shows socket high anomalies, and carts shows diskio values equal to its global P95/P5 (zero). Earliest anomalous points for many groups start around 2024-01-20T07:05Z. Because multiple services show anomalies, we need to (1) confirm which of the five candidate services actually have consecutive faults (not isolated points) during the window, and (2) use traces/logs to identify the most downstream faulty service when multiple services are faulty. The next atomic step is to produce a compact anomaly summary limited to the five candidate services so we can identify which service-KPI series contain sustained faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, restrict rows to the incident window 2024-01-20 07:02:05 UTC — 2024-01-20 07:32:05 UTC and to cmdb_id in [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"]. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 using the full series for that group (do NOT compute thresholds using only filtered rows). Then detect anomalies in the incident window: 'high' if value >= global P95, 'low' if value <= global P5. For each group and anomaly_type return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_type, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, min_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Sort by anomaly_count descending and limit to top 50 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "The trace check returned no trace telemetry for the candidate services (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) in the incident window. Therefore we cannot use traces to pick the most-downstream faulty service. We must rely on metrics (already showing strong signals for orders: sustained high errors and prolonged diskio=0 runs) and logs to localize the root cause and reason. Next step is to inspect log telemetry: aggregated normalized logs (log.csv) to see which services show abnormal log KPIs during the window and textual error logs (error_logs.csv) to find concrete error messages for candidate services. These will help confirm whether orders experienced I/O/disk issues or if another service is the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From log.csv: filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-20 07:02:05 UTC — 2024-01-20 07:32:05 UTC and cmdb_id in [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"]. Aggregate by (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full available series to compute global P95 and P5 for each (do NOT compute thresholds from filtered rows). Then for the filtered rows, for each (cmdb_id, log_name) produce: count_in_window, earliest_timestamp_in_window, latest_timestamp_in_window, min_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, mean_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5. Return rows sorted by count_in_window descending and limit to top 50.\n\nFrom error_logs.csv: filter rows to the same incident window and same cmdb_id list, and return up to 50 rows with columns (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) sorted by timestamp ascending. If no rows exist, return an explicit empty indicator." }

I reviewed the metric and log analysis steps: orders showed brief abnormal disk I/O spikes around 07:05 followed by a prolonged run of diskio = 0 from ~07:07 to ~07:29, concurrently with a sustained increase in orders.error across the same interval. No trace data was available and logs did not contradict the metrics. This pattern indicates the Orders service experienced an I/O-related failure that caused increased errors.

